83
00:04:44,382 --> 00:04:46,583
in terms of the materials,

84
00:04:46,583 --> 00:04:51,493
is that the spectrum of the neutrons
is quite different.

85
00:04:51,493 --> 00:04:53,448
So in fission,

86
00:04:53,448 --> 00:04:56,363
if we take the average
of the neutron energy,

87
00:04:56,363 --> 00:05:00,570
typically of the order of 2 MeV,

88
00:05:00,570 --> 00:05:06,300
whereas in fusion, as we know,
the neutrons are produced at 14.1 MeV,

89
00:05:06,300 --> 00:05:10,378
from the DT reaction.
So we have a much higher energy.

90
00:05:11,228 --> 00:05:16,528
Much higher energy for the neutrons,
which translates into a higher activation,

91
00:05:16,528 --> 00:05:18,627
but, even more important,

92
00:05:18,627 --> 00:05:22,562
to a higher degradation
of the material properties.

93
00:05:23,465 --> 00:05:27,610
Let's evaluate very simply,
first, the mechanical effects

94
00:05:27,610 --> 00:05:32,924
of the neutrons, that they can have
on the material atoms in the lattice,

95
00:05:33,472 --> 00:05:39,782
So, take a neutron of energy En
that hits an atom of mass M,

96
00:05:39,799 --> 00:05:42,173
which is at rest in the lattice.

97
00:05:42,173 --> 00:05:45,383
We consider sort of a 1D situation,

98
00:05:45,383 --> 00:05:47,988
that's my neutron,

99
00:05:48,478 --> 00:05:53,188
we have a velocity that is associated
with its energy,

100
00:05:55,328 --> 00:05:59,624
and it will hit an atom M,
I draw it bigger

101
00:05:59,624 --> 00:06:02,867
because the atom will be, of course,
of a larger mass

102
00:06:03,317 --> 00:06:05,598
that we suppose to be
at rest in the lattice.

103
00:06:05,598 --> 00:06:07,171
And now we evaluate,

104
00:06:07,171 --> 00:06:11,266
based on a very simple theory
of elastic collisions,

105
00:06:11,266 --> 00:06:14,771
that is, collisions that conserve energy
and momentum,

106
00:06:14,771 --> 00:06:19,405
the maximum energy transfer
in this event.

107
00:06:19,405 --> 00:06:24,858
So the maximum energy transfer,
let's call it Emax,

108
00:06:24,858 --> 00:06:29,447
is given by the energy of the neutron
times four times the product of the masses

109
00:06:29,447 --> 00:06:31,879
divided by the square
of the sum of the masses.

110
00:06:31,879 --> 00:06:34,848
This is really simple
elastic collisions theory.

111
00:06:34,848 --> 00:06:36,964
Now, the mass of the neutron
is much smaller

112
00:06:36,964 --> 00:06:39,629
than the mass of our atom,

113
00:06:39,629 --> 00:06:42,469
so we can write that's equal to En,
energy of the neutron,

114
00:06:42,469 --> 00:06:46,114
times four times its mass
divided by the mass of the atom.

115
00:06:46,114 --> 00:06:48,988
Let's take now numbers, examples.

116
00:06:48,988 --> 00:06:54,538
I'll take Iron, so M

117
00:06:54,538 --> 00:06:58,100
is 56 atomic mass units (amu)

118
00:06:58,100 --> 00:07:01,602
and I'll take a neutron
issued by a fusion reaction,

119
00:07:01,602 --> 00:07:05,648
that is a neutron
with an energy of 14.1 MeV.

120
00:07:05,648 --> 00:07:09,047
The max energy transfer, Emax,

121
00:07:09,047 --> 00:07:13,486
will be 14.1 x 10⁶,

122
00:07:13,486 --> 00:07:18,486
times 4 divided by 56,
that's about 1 MeV.

123
00:07:18,490 --> 00:07:21,711
We notice this energy is very large,

124
00:07:21,711 --> 00:07:24,848
and it is, indeed, much higher

125
00:07:24,848 --> 00:07:28,226
than the so-called Wigner energy,

126
00:07:28,226 --> 00:07:33,386
which is typically about 25 eV.

127
00:07:33,415 --> 00:07:38,865
This Wigner energy is the threshold value

128
00:07:38,865 --> 00:07:43,229
for the energy at which we have
a displacement of an atom.

129
00:07:43,229 --> 00:07:48,779
So this is the <i>threshold
displacement energy</i>.

130
00:07:49,369 --> 00:07:53,536
So that means that the Iron atom

131
00:07:53,536 --> 00:07:56,836
will be displaced
and ejected from the lattice.

132
00:08:08,111 --> 00:08:13,201
And because this energy
that is exchanged in a collision

133
00:08:13,201 --> 00:08:17,431
is much larger than the Wigner energy,
much, much larger,

134
00:08:17,431 --> 00:08:22,231
this primary atom that is displaced,
called the <i>primary knock-on atom</i>,

135
00:08:22,233 --> 00:08:25,757
will initiate a series
of other knock-on events.

136
00:08:25,757 --> 00:08:28,822
And that will lead to what we call
an atomic displacement cascade.

137
00:08:28,822 --> 00:08:33,629
So it's sort of a shower
of displacements across my material.

138
00:08:33,629 --> 00:08:37,511
And this is shown
in the simulation here.

139
00:08:37,511 --> 00:08:38,987
So the result is that we have

140
00:08:38,987 --> 00:08:42,662
a series of so-called
<i>point structure defects</i>

141
00:08:42,662 --> 00:08:46,191
because the ejected atom
will leave behind a vacancy,

142
00:08:46,891 --> 00:08:51,411
that is, a hole, there.

143
00:08:52,878 --> 00:08:58,868
And it will go somewhere
where it doesn't belong to,

144
00:08:58,879 --> 00:09:03,409
and that somewhere is called
an <i>interstitial location</i>.

145
00:09:04,929 --> 00:09:08,447
The pair formed by the vacancy
and interstitial location

146
00:09:08,447 --> 00:09:10,503
is called a <i>Frenkel pair</i>.

147
00:09:10,503 --> 00:09:14,932
Now this sort of effect,
I can call it damage

148
00:09:14,932 --> 00:09:18,666
because it damages the 
properties of the material

149
00:09:18,666 --> 00:09:23,476
is quantified in a unit called <i>dpa</i>,
or displacements per atom.

150
00:09:23,476 --> 00:09:26,364
So this is the average number
of displacements

151
00:09:26,364 --> 00:09:29,320
that the atom undergoes
under the irradiation.

152
00:09:30,610 --> 00:09:33,888
That was sort of the mechanical effect
of the neutron

153
00:09:33,888 --> 00:09:36,629
hitting the atoms in the lattice,

154
00:09:36,629 --> 00:09:38,902
but the neutron will also cause
nuclear reactions,

155
00:09:38,902 --> 00:09:40,885
in particular transmutations.

156
00:09:40,885 --> 00:09:48,265
These reactions will generate impurities
in the form of helium or hydrogen gas.

157
00:09:48,877 --> 00:09:53,570
And the creation of gas
inside the material lattice

158
00:09:53,570 --> 00:09:55,960
will result in embrittlement,

159
00:09:55,960 --> 00:09:58,278
embrittlement of grain boundaries,
in particular,

160
00:09:58,278 --> 00:10:01,055
and swelling of the voids.

161
00:10:01,745 --> 00:10:04,240
So here the problem is
the generation

162
00:10:04,240 --> 00:10:06,472
of helium and hydrogen impurities,

163
00:10:06,472 --> 00:10:11,100
and so this effect is quantified
in atomic parts-per-million

164
00:10:11,100 --> 00:10:14,813
of helium or hydrogen, or <i>appm</i>.

165
00:10:14,813 --> 00:10:17,153
So we have the displacement per atom,

166
00:10:17,153 --> 00:10:21,709
<i>dpa</i>, that quantifies the mechanical damage

167
00:10:21,709 --> 00:10:26,167
and atomic parts-per-million
resulting from the nuclear reactions

168
00:10:26,167 --> 00:10:31,147
of helium or hydrogen
that quantify the effect of transmutations.

169
00:10:33,908 --> 00:10:37,961
So we do have important modifications
of the microstructure

170
00:10:37,961 --> 00:10:39,700
and these modifications

171
00:10:39,700 --> 00:10:43,833
will lead to a significant degradation
of the macroscopic properties,

172
00:10:43,833 --> 00:10:46,964
chemical, physical, and mechanical.

173
00:10:46,964 --> 00:10:51,745
Here is again a figure that represents
a sequence of possible events,

174
00:10:51,745 --> 00:10:54,258
the creation of a Frenkel pair,

175
00:10:54,258 --> 00:10:57,734
that is, a vacancy
and an interstitial location,

176
00:10:57,734 --> 00:11:00,040
and a transmutation

177
00:11:00,040 --> 00:11:04,678
and also the migration of these defects
across my lattice.

178
00:11:04,678 --> 00:11:07,384
And just to give you an example
of orders of magnitude

179
00:11:07,384 --> 00:11:09,549
of the numbers involved
in a fusion reactor,

180
00:11:09,549 --> 00:11:15,069
let's take a fusion reactor
with a fusion power of 3GW.

181
00:11:15,752 --> 00:11:20,612
That will lead to
a neutron irradiation effect

182
00:11:20,612 --> 00:11:25,310
of say, 20 to 30 dpa per year in steels.

